node.text:
Social distancing circles are by now a common sight. By painting these circles with different permutations and combinations for different family sizes that shall be coming to such public spaces, in this instance, Marine Drive, with each cluster placed apart from the other at a distance of 2 metres or 6 feet we can provide flexibility to the end users while also making a provision for safety. Separate zones along the promenade can be created with circles marked at social distancing standards of 2m or 6 feet and allowed for different activities during different times of the day. 
For example- From 6am to 8am this zone can be reserved for morning yoga and workout for the public. The same markers can be used during the day/night for hawkers standing/sitting or visitors engaging in conversation with their peers. With clear visual indication, the arriving pedestrians can ascertain whether the public space is utilised to its optimum strength and alerting them in making an informed decision.

node.text:
Thoughtful summer essential...
WHY SILK?
cos its GULNAZ AMIN ! 
Actually theres more....
1) its hypoallergenic naturally: 
even its makers – the silkworms – weave their cocoons into safety shields against the dust mites. The proteins in silk repel these microscopic critters, which, coincidentally, are among the leading causes of human allergies.

2)Helps with eczema and asthma: silk has shown to be more compatible with even the worst cases of skin allergy because of its 100% organic origin.
Another of its great feature: silk prevents the build-up of soil, dirt, and other microscopic foreign bodies that may trigger an allergy, especially in people with eczema. Thanks to these healing properties, we can now wear it all day long on the FACE ITSELF as theres another GREATEST REASON:

3) IT SLOWS DOWN AGING : 
it is a natural material packed with essential amino acids and natural protein, silk tricks the nervous system into relaxing; therefore smoothening out the wrinkles we develop through age.
With albumen, a naturally-occurring chemical in silk, the skin’s metabolism speeds up, allowing dead skin cells to develop and repair at a much faster rate.  Over time, the long-term use of silk will drastically improve the skin’s appearance, significantly slowing down the effects of ageing

DO YOU NEED MORE REASONS? ...
Choose silk over polyester....

When it comes to indian wear, there is no ignoring the life long  love affair with flowy crepe sarees. But well it's time to give this affair a fresh new spin by adding a belt to my naive, all plain turquoise saree. Twirl my way through the day with this beautiful saree.  I tried this drape in the very first few days of lockdown. Crepe is my personal favorite, there is no hassle I  draping the smooth, soft, flowing fabric. And no chance of it to crumple  like silk and cotton. Easy things always attract me(the lazy me).

Workwear Look book Part II
I loved to wear Indian outfit piece to work. Just don’t wear your Salwar suit everyday... Try to add pieces like palazzo pants, straight pants, short kurthis and especially saree 🥻You can never go wrong with a saree 😀👍 Look 1 
Paired printed palazzo pant @bibaindia with a shirt dress as jacket @targetstyle 
Look 2
Bengal cotton saree @tulsisilks I have grown seeing my mom wear bengal cotton saree almost everyday to work. I feel it gives a very smart and powerful look. It is a bit tricky to drape, but once you get a hang of it, you will rock it 😊
Look 3
Black palazzo bottom @bibaindia with cotton tops @lifestylestores Added a belt and black boots.
Look 4
Linen Kurta @lifestylestores with blue jeans @americaneagle You cannot go more basic than this 😊
Look 5
